    ðŸ”¹ 1. Control Plane Components
        These manage the overall cluster state.
        âœ… API Server (kube-apiserver)
            Entry point for all Kubernetes commands (kubectl, REST API, other components).
            Validates and processes API requests.
            Stores the desired state in etcd.
        âœ… etcd
            A distributed key-value store.
            Stores all cluster data (desired + current state).
            Example: deployments, pod definitions, config maps, secrets.
            Highly available (usually deployed as a cluster).
        âœ… Controller Manager (kube-controller-manager)
            Runs background controllers that ensure the desired state = current state.
            Examples:
            Node controller â†’ Monitors node health.
            Replication controller â†’ Ensures correct number of pod replicas.
            Endpoint controller â†’ Manages service endpoints.
        âœ… Scheduler (kube-scheduler)
            Decides which node runs a new Pod.
            Considers:
            Resource requests (CPU, memory).
            Affinity/anti-affinity rules.
            Taints/tolerations.
            Workload balancing.
    ðŸ”¹ 2. Worker Node Components
        These run the actual application workloads.
        âœ… Kubelet
            Agent running on each node.
            Communicates with the API server.
            Ensures containers in pods are running as expected (via container runtime).
        âœ… Kube-proxy
            Manages network rules on each node.
            Enables service discovery and routing.
            Handles traffic load-balancing to backend pods.
        âœ… Container Runtime
            The actual engine that runs containers.
            Examples: containerd, CRI-O, Docker (deprecated for kubelet).